cff-version: 1.2.0
message: "If you cite the Chimère Ω blueprint paper, please use this form."
title: "Chimère Ω: a blueprint for a physico-cognitively inspired local-first LLM runtime with entropic mode scheduling"
authors:
  - family-names: Remondière
    given-names: Kevin
    orcid: "https://orcid.org/0009-0008-2443-7166"
    affiliation: "Independent Researcher"
type: article
repository-code: "https://github.com/AIdevsmartdata/crossed-cosmos"
url: "https://github.com/AIdevsmartdata/crossed-cosmos/tree/master/paper/chimere_omega"
abstract: >-
  We propose Chimère Ω, a blueprint for a local-first LLM runtime that
  allocates computation across four modes — fast prediction, block-diffusion
  refinement, symbolic verification, latent-space planning — via a
  scheduler driven by token-level residual entropy. The blueprint
  integrates verified Q4 2025 – Q2 2026 state-of-the-art (LeJEPA/SIGReg,
  hybrid GDN + sparse-attention backbones, Titans / Nested Learning
  memory, Block-Diffusion BD3, auxiliary-loss-free MoE routing, vLLM V1
  + EAGLE-3 stack) with three design hypotheses framed as falsifiable
  statements inspired by the author's ECI framework. The physics
  inspiration is used as analogical scaffolding, not mathematical
  derivation; this distinction is enforced throughout. Phase 1 of the
  24-month roadmap is immediately executable on consumer hardware
  (RTX 5060 Ti, 16 GB VRAM) via the author's existing chimere-server
  Rust FFI runtime.
keywords:
  - LLM runtime
  - mixture of experts
  - block diffusion
  - JEPA world models
  - persistent memory
  - entropic scheduling
  - physico-cognitive architecture
  - consumer hardware
  - open-weights
